3.1 Basic Objects (Structs)

A struct (short for structure) is a user-defined data type that allows you to group multiple variables (data members) into a single entity. It was originally designed to mimic the functionality of the built-in array data types, but with the added flexibility of adding additional data members. In C++, a struct is defined using the struct keyword, followed by the name of the struct, and then the data members enclosed in curly braces.

Example:

```
struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    float height;
};

// This is equivalent to:
// struct Person {
//     string name;
//     int age;
//     float height;
// };
```

If you would like to have a constructor when you create a new object, you need to place the constructor inside the curly brackets. For example:

```
struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    float height;

    Person(string n, int a, float h) : name(n), age(a), height(h) {}
};
```

You can then create an object using the constructor:

```
Person p("John Doe", 25, 5.11);
```

3.2 Assignment of Objects

You can assign one object to another object of the same type using the = operator. This will copy all of the data members from the source object into the destination object.

Example:

```
struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    float height;
};

// Define an object "p1"
Person p1("John Doe", 25, 5.11);

// Define a new object "p2"
Person p2;

// Assign "p1" to "p2"
p2 = p1;
```

3.3 . and -> Operators

In C++, you can access (and modify) the data members of a struct or a class using either the . or -> operators.

Example:

```
struct Person {
    string name;
    int age;
    float height;
};

// Define an object "p"
Person p("John Doe", 25, 5.11);

// Access the 'name' data member
cout << p.name << endl;

// Access the 'age' data member
cout << p.age << endl;

// Access the 'height' data member
cout << p.height << endl;

// You can also use the -> operator
// to access the data members
// of an object pointer
Person* pp = &p;

// Access the 'name' data member
cout << pp->name << endl;

// Access the 'age' data member
cout << pp->age << endl;

// Access the 'height' data member
cout << pp->height << endl;
```

3.4 Use of getline()

In C++, you can read an entire line from the standard input (keyboard) using the `getline()` function. This function will read an entire line from the input stream, and store it in a `string` object.

Example:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main()
{
    string line;
    getline(cin, line);

    cout << "You entered: " << line << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

3.5 Checking an Input Stream for Failure

You can check whether the input stream failed to read a value by calling the `fail()` function on the input stream object. This function will return `true` if the input stream has failed, and `false` if it has succeeded.

Example:

```
#include <iostream>

int main()
{
    int x;

    cin >> x;

    if (cin.fail()) {
        cout << "Input failed!" << endl;
    } else {
        cout << "Input succeeded!" << endl;
        cout << "You entered: " << x << endl;
    }

    return 0;
}
```

3.6 Using C++ String Class

In C++, you can use the `string` class to work with strings of characters. This class provides many useful methods for manipulating strings, including converting strings to other types, searching for substrings, and formatting strings.

Example:

```
#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main()
{
    string s1 = "Hello, World!";
    string s2 = s1;

    // Convert a string to an integer
    int x = stoi(s1);

    // Convert a string to a float
    float y = stof(s2);

    // Find the position of a substring
    string find = "World";
    size_t pos = s1.find(find);

    // Replace a substring
    s1.replace(pos, find.size(), "Goodbye");

    // Search for a substring
    string substr = s1.substr(5, 9);

    // Format a string
    string format = "Your input was: %d";
    cout << format << endl;
    cout << format << x << endl;

    cout << s1 << endl;

    return 0;
}
```

