5.3 Efficiency of various operations given variations of their implementation (with or without tail pointer, etc)

The efficiency of linked list operations can depend on the implementation of the list. For example, if you do not have a tail pointer, then you cannot perform constant-time operations like pushing and popping from the back of the list.

Example:

```
// LinkedList.h
#ifndef LINKEDLIST_H
#define LINKEDLIST_H

template <typename T>
class Node {
    T data;
    Node<T>* next;

public:
